## Propagating Trace Context Through RabbitMQ Headers

The key is to inject the current `Activity` context into message headers on publish, then extract and restore it on consume.

**Publisher (Service A):**

```csharp
using System.Diagnostics;
using OpenTelemetry;
using OpenTelemetry.Context.Propagation;
using RabbitMQ.Client;

// Start an activity for the publish operation
using var activity = ActivitySource.StartActivity("OrderEvent Publish", ActivityKind.Producer);

var props = channel.CreateBasicProperties();
props.Headers ??= new Dictionary<string, object>();

// Inject current context into message headers
Propagators.DefaultTextMapPropagator.Inject(
    new PropagationContext(activity.Context, Baggage.Current),
    props.Headers,
    (headers, key, value) => headers[key] = value);

channel.BasicPublish(exchange, routingKey, props, body);
```

**Consumer (Service B):**

```csharp
using System.Diagnostics;
using OpenTelemetry;
using OpenTelemetry.Context.Propagation;

// Extract context from incoming message headers
var parentContext = Propagators.DefaultTextMapPropagator.Extract(
    default,
    ea.BasicProperties.Headers,
    (headers, key) =>
    {
        if (headers.TryGetValue(key, out var value) && value is byte[] bytes)
            return new[] { System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetString(bytes) };
        return Enumerable.Empty<string>();
    });

// Restore baggage and start a linked activity
Baggage.Current = parentContext.Baggage;
using var activity = ActivitySource.StartActivity(
    "OrderEvent Process",
    ActivityKind.Consumer,
    parentContext.ActivityContext);
```

**Why the `byte[]` cast?** RabbitMQ's .NET client stores header values as `byte[]`, not `string`.

**OTel SDK setup (both services):**

```csharp
builder.Services.AddOpenTelemetry()
    .WithTracing(t => t
        .AddSource("YourApp.ActivitySourceName")
        .AddOtlpExporter());
```

This gives you a single end-to-end trace with the consumer span parented to the producer span across the queue boundary.
